    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1539865133" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1539865133" />
    <a title="Stephen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8201780-stephen"><img alt="Stephen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1412473145p2/8201780.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1539865133?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen" href="/user/show/8201780-stephen">Stephen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780345431622" href="/book/show/323172.Mockingbird">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1539865133" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1036066102913325798">I&apos;d never heard of Walter Tevis until I read this novel. <i>Mockingbird</i> left me curious of Tevis&apos; background given it reads as a very personal indictment of illiteracy, sloth, drugs and religion. Turns out <i>Mockingbird</i> was Tevis&apos; only foray into science fiction. He is better known for his novels turned into popular films: The Hustler, The Color of Money and the Man Who Fell to Earth.<br/><br/><i>Mockingbird</i> presents a dystopian future New York where humans have been taught by robots they created to become privat</span>
  <span id="freeText1036066102913325798" style="display:none">I'd never heard of Walter Tevis until I read this novel. <i>Mockingbird</i> left me curious of Tevis' background given it reads as a very personal indictment of illiteracy, sloth, drugs and religion. Turns out <i>Mockingbird</i> was Tevis' only foray into science fiction. He is better known for his novels turned into popular films: The Hustler, The Color of Money and the Man Who Fell to Earth.<br /><br /><i>Mockingbird</i> presents a dystopian future New York where humans have been taught by robots they created to become private, inwardly focused and passive to the point where asking questions, speaking and touching one another are criminal offenses. The entire population is illiterate, hooked on drugs (sopors) and television, and using 1960's vernacular "zoned out." No one questions this reality until one day Paul Bentley finds some elementary school readers and teaches himself to read.<br /><br />Tevis wrote <i>Mockingbird</i> in 1980, reportedly reacting to declining literacy rates of students at Ohio University where he taught. One can imagine that Tevis saw in the late 1970s-early 1908s MTV generation the doom of civilization.<br /><br />Enter Bob Sopporth, Make 9 robot, hyper intelligent, fully conscious and capable of feelings, created to serve a mankind he no longer finds worth saving. In despair he only wants to die, but cannot until the last human is gone. Paul Bentley's sudden awareness is at first a hopeful sign that all is not lost. As is Paul finding the even more independent Mary Lou. Can Paul and Mary Lou save the human race and rescue Bob or will Bob destroy both to end his existence?<br /><br /><i>Mockingbird</i> holds up reasonably well for being almost 40 years old. Its central theme of reading leads to awareness of not just facts but also feelings, beauty and love that is creatively explored. That said, I enjoyed the first half--Bob, Paul and Mary meeting each other--much more than the second half which drags through Paul's continuing self discovery and becomes outright "preachy" against Christianity. Tevis' view is clear when he/Paul concludes that God is like a judgmental robot; Jesus was on the right track but his followers failed to instill his message of tolerance and kindness. Tevis' attempt at a happy ending was predictable and did little to balance what for the later half of the novel read like an evangelist (irony intended) extorting the masses to wake up or we're all doomed.<br /><br />On my buy, borrow or skip scale, I rate <i>Mockingbird</i> a weak borrow.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1036066102913325798" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


