<div id="review_2624321426" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2624321426" />
    <a title="Jamie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53587416-jamie"><img alt="Jamie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624318899p2/53587416.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2624321426?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie" href="/user/show/53587416-jamie">Jamie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/41618151-mockingbird">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2624321426" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17261922610413350487">Interesting post-apocalyptic story, although I found the prose and narrative structure overly plain, lacking much style or depth. The story deals with both the dumbing down of society through drugs and television, reminiscent of C.M. Kornbluth&apos;s classic The Marching Morons, as well as widespread sterility and a dwindling population. People have been conditioned to become emotionally and socially isolated and detached, making them easier to control and manage, and are no longer even literate. Thu</span>
  <span id="freeText17261922610413350487" style="display:none">Interesting post-apocalyptic story, although I found the prose and narrative structure overly plain, lacking much style or depth. The story deals with both the dumbing down of society through drugs and television, reminiscent of C.M. Kornbluth's classic The Marching Morons, as well as widespread sterility and a dwindling population. People have been conditioned to become emotionally and socially isolated and detached, making them easier to control and manage, and are no longer even literate. Thus, society comes to rely upon robots more and more to function. But at some point the knowledge and expertise to build and repair the robots is lost, and society begins to fall apart. The story follows a man, a woman and a robot, known as a Make Nine, which is an intelligent human/robot cyborg, as they awaken from their conditioned stupor and try to regain some semblance of their lost humanity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17261922610413350487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

